Name: MAUREEN E. FLANNERY
Locality: South Salmon Creek Beach, ~200 yds south of Bean Avenue entrance
Additional Remarks: Probable Orca Attack. On 18 May 2016, a report came out in the Press Democrat online with a video of a pod of 4-6 Orca attacking a Gray Whale calf with it's mother on 14 May 2016 along the Sonoma Coast off of Carmet Beach. Based on video stills and photos from this carcass on the beach, as well as the many rake marks on the carcass, it was most likely the same animal in both the orca attack on 14 May 2016 and the carcass on the beach on 16 May 2016.

Name: MAUREEN E. FLANNERY
Locality: Daly City, Westmoor Beach at Daisaku Ikeda Canyon
CauseOfDeathOtherRemarks: ship strike see comments for details.
Additional Remarks: Carcass was first reported to TMMC on 10/26/16 at 12:30 flotaing about 0.25 mile off shore of Daly City.  Later that  day the carcass was reported on land approximately 0.5 mile north of Muscesll Rock (37.67943 N, 122.496278W) at 17:30. A compete necropsy was completed on 10/27/16 by TMMC and CAS.  Additional participants:  UC Davis, Point Blue Conservation Science and Oceanic Society.  Please se Necropsy Report for compete details.   Brief summary of necropsy finidngs: fractured skull and various focal areas of necrotic tissue consistent with blunt foce trauma, likely from a ship strike.

Name: MAUREEN E. FLANNERY
Locality: Oakland Harbor
Additional Remarks: identified as a fin whale (Balenoptera physalus) by asymmetrical coloration on madibles (gray righ mandilbe) and throat groves, bicolored baleen, overall coloration. And genetics from SWFSC.  Animal was originally reported by the US Coast Guard at Yerba Buena Island 1/5/17 when a vessel, NYK Triton, had what appeared to be a whale-sized animal or possible whale carcass on the bow of the ship as the vessel turned into Oakland Bar Channel it fell  off bow of boat and sank.  The whale was then reported on 1/7/17 floating in Oakland Harbor off Howard Terminal. Two personnel from TMMC went out to assess the animal , take pictures, and collect a couple of basic samples.  Due to a storm with large swells, high winds, and rainfall, the animal was left floating  next to the Howard Termnal.   The USCG got a report of the animal floating in the Oakland Harbor Channel on 1/9/17 causing a hazard to passing vessels.  The animal was towed to Angel Island by the Army Corps of Engineers where it was tied off a pier near Blunt Point until weather conditions improved.  Due to repeated intense weather and storm debris clean-up the Army Corp of Engineers was only able to land the carcass on Angel Island on 1/25/17.  Due to continued bad weather and boat availability a small team was un unable to get to the caracss for a partial carcass for a partial necropsy on 2/6/17.  See the necropsy report for more details.

Name: MAUREEN E. FLANNERY
Locality: Agate Beach, approximately 0.25 miles north of the parking lot
CauseOfDeathOtherRemarks: ship strike see comments for details.
Additional Remarks: The carcass was originally reported as floating off of Agate Beach in Marin County, the evening of 25 May 2017.  The carcass was confirmed on land at Agate Beach (37.899783N, 122.712575 W) the morning of 26 May 2017.  Due to the timing of the tides and logistics, three researchers from TMMC and CAS examined the carcass on 5/26/2017.  The carcass was identified as a known animal, CRC-1540, by Cascadia Research Collective on 5/26/2017.  CRC-1540 was first identified off California in 1999 and seen in at least 11 diffferent years off California mostly in the Santa Barbara Channel area.  Genetic confrimation on the match can be made from a biopsy taken in 2006.  She wa documented with a calf in two years.  There may be additional sighting informatioon from the Sea of Cortez, Mexico since she also matches the CICMAR Catalog.

Name: MAUREEN E. FLANNERY
Locality: on the beach north of Slide Ranch
Additional Remarks: This animal was reported  floating off shore late Sunday night 10/7/18.  The carcass washed ashore on 10/8/18 just north of Slide Ranch Near Muir Beach.  Due to the tides, the necropsy team was not able to access he whale until Thursday morning 10/11/18 and by then the carcass was rolling in the surf.  Some estimated lengths were takesn as well as skin and skull frgments; but a full necropsy could not be performed.  There were skull fragments found on the beach wher the whale had been stranded the evening before.

Name: MAUREEN E. FLANNERY
Locality: Rodeo Marina floating offshore near the Phillips 66
Additional Remarks: This animal was initially reported on 4/2 to be floating off shore near the Phillips< Lat: This animal was initially reported on 4/2 to be floating offshore near the Phillips 66 Refinery in Rodeo, CA and drifing towards  the Carquinez Bridge.  There were no towing services availabe at the time so th carcass was left to float.  On 4/3 the carcass was markedly bloated and floating a the mouoth of a marina near Rodeo Creek.  A team was assembled in cas of a potential necropsy. However once the team got there, the whale was still floating and even with a lower tide the carcass was inaccessible.  The team tied off the whale that evening.  On 4/4 Parker Diving Service and a team from TMMC towed the whale to Angel Island.  At this point in time the animal was still in relatively fresh condition. Due to the timing of tides, weather and dayligh hours the necropsy was postponed untile Tuesday April 9.  On 4/9 the animal was high and dry, but now was in moderate state of decomposition.

Name: MAUREEN E. FLANNERY
Locality: Pacifica, North End of Sharp Park Beach
Additional Remarks: First Reported the morning of April 16th,  floating off the Thorton State Beach, Daly City .  The carcas reached land at Esplanade Beach that afternoon and was tied off by a TMMC volunteer (Lat: 37.64862 long -122.496812.)  The carcass floated further sout to Manor overnight where it was necropsied the next day.  See the necropsy report for more details.

Name: MAUREEN E. FLANNERY
Locality: Brooks Island Regional Preserve
Additional Remarks: The Carcass was first reported floating off of Point Molate the morning of April 13, 2019.  On April 13 at 5:37  p.m. it was reported on Red Rock Island south of the Richmond Bridge. On April 14 It was reported by some boaters as floating in SF Bay at 37.87265N,  122.39953W.  It was not seen for two days and was then reported on landon Brooks Island on April 16.  The carcass was amputed posterior to the genital slit and was missing the entire peduncle and flukes based on measurment of the remaining carcass (910 cm) and similar sized female gray whales, we estimate the intact carcass would have been approximately 12m in length.  See necropsy report for more details.

Name: MAUREEN E. FLANNERY
Locality: Angel Isalnd State Park,

Name: MAUREEN E. FLANNERY
Locality: Point Reyes National Seashore, Limantour Beach, 0.25 miles west of the trail from parking  lot
Additional Remarks: The animal was first reported on Sunday, April 28th, floating offshore of Limantour Beach (Lat.38.019880, long. -122.898004.)  The whale fully came on shore later that evening on the high tide.  The carcas was reported still on Limnatour beach on 29 April 2019.  We coordinated the necropsy with PRNS and the snowy plover biologist.  There were plovers that were nesting in both directions on the beach and we were instructed not to let any pieces float away.  Because of this request,we could not fully get into the abdomnial or the thoracic cavity to assess further.  A team from PRNS, TMMC, and CAS preformed a necropsy on 30 April 2019. Thjere was one partial and one full thickness laceration along the caudel peduncle and a partial thickness laceration along the dorsal aspect of the fluke,  see necropsy report for more details.

Name: DENISE J. GREIG
Locality: Ocean Beach, just south of Balboa Street between Stairwell 4 &5
Additional Remarks: A Beach Watch volunteer  called in the carcass on 7/8/19.  She was concerend that a round hole in the right shoulder was a gunshot wound.  I spoke with TMMC and considered requesting help with an xray, but decided it was more likely scavenging .  Thre was another hold, caudal to the first and alon the dorsal midline.  And someholes near the ankles on the ventral side.  The skin/blubber was cut away from the dorsal holes and no evidence of a gunshot track or tissue hemorrhage was noted.  The flippers were missing some bones and partially mummified and the face was scavanged (eyes and ear areas missing) I did not open up the main body cavity.  Beach Watch attached a piece of pink and white fabric to the left rear flipper.  CAS attached a piece of green twin to the left front flipper.
